    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How deep should fence posts be?</summary>
        <p>The general rule is to bury one-third of the total post length. For a standard 6-foot privacy fence using 8-foot posts, that means burying 2 to 2.5 feet deep. In areas with frost, posts should extend below the frost line to prevent heaving, which can be 36 to 48 inches deep in northern climates. Setting posts in concrete further improves stability, especially for gate posts and corner posts that bear additional stress from hardware and lateral force.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How far apart should fence posts be?</summary>
        <p>Standard fence post spacing is 8 feet on center for most wood fence styles, which matches the common rail length of 8 feet. Some fence types use 6-foot spacing for extra strength, particularly in high-wind areas or for fences taller than 6 feet. Chain-link fences typically use 10-foot post spacing. Gate posts should be spaced to match the desired gate width plus approximately 1 inch of clearance for hardware.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the best wood for fences?</summary>
        <p>Cedar and redwood are the most popular choices because they are naturally rot-resistant and insect-resistant without chemical treatment. Pressure-treated pine is the most affordable option and lasts 15 to 20 years with proper maintenance. For premium durability, white oak and black locust are exceptionally rot-resistant hardwoods that can last 25+ years. The best choice depends on your budget, climate, and aesthetic preference. In humid climates, natural rot resistance is especially valuable.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need a permit to build a fence?</summary>
        <p>In most municipalities, yes, you need a permit for fences above a certain height, typically 6 feet in the backyard and 3 to 4 feet in the front yard. Permit requirements vary by location, so check with your local building department before starting. You may also need to comply with HOA rules, setback requirements, and the good-neighbor provision that requires the finished side to face outward. Building without a permit can result in fines, required modifications, or forced removal.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How much does a fence cost per linear foot?</summary>
        <p>Costs vary widely by material and style. Wood privacy fences typically cost $15 to $35 per linear foot for materials, or $25 to $60 installed by a contractor. Vinyl fences range from $20 to $40 for materials, $30 to $70 installed. Chain-link is the most affordable at $7 to $15 for materials, $12 to $30 installed. Cedar and composite fencing fall at the higher end. Gate installation adds $150 to $600 per gate depending on size and style. Use our <a href="/calculators/construction/fence-calculator/">fence calculator</a> to estimate materials and costs for your specific project.</p>
      </details>
